  "ShortQuestions": [
    {
      "id": 1,
      "question": "Why is the alt attribute so important? Give three reasons.",
      "preferredAnswer": "1. **Accessibility:** Screen readers read the alt text aloud to visually impaired users.\n2. **Broken Images:** If an image fails to load, the alt text is displayed in its place.\n3. **SEO:** Search engines rely on alt text to understand what the image shows."
    },
    {
      "id": 2,
      "question": "Explain the difference between <div> and <span> with a practical example of each.",
      "preferredAnswer": "**<div>** is a **block-level** container (full width, new line). Used to group large sections.\n**<span>** is an **inline** container (stays within text flow). Used to target specific words or phrases.\n\nExample: `<p>The price is <span>$49.99</span> per month.</p>`\nNeither has semantic meaning — they exist for CSS targeting and grouping."
    },
    {
      "id": 3,
      "question": "You have pages/about.html and images/team.jpg at the same level. Write the correct <img> tag to display team.jpg from about.html.",
      "preferredAnswer": "```html\n<img src=\"../images/team.jpg\" alt=\"Our team photo\" width=\"600\" height=\"400\">\n```\nFrom `pages/about.html`, we go **up one level** (`../`) to reach the root, then into `images/` to find `team.jpg`."
    },
    {
      "id": 4,
      "question": "What is <figure> and <figcaption>? When would you use them instead of just <img> alone?",
      "preferredAnswer": "`<figure>` is a semantic container that groups an image with its `<figcaption>` (caption). Use them when an image needs a **visible caption** that explains or credits the image. Use `<img>` alone when the image doesn't need a visible caption (icons, logos, decorative images)."
    },
    {
      "id": 5,
      "question": "What is \"div soup\" and why should you avoid it? How can you fix it?",
      "preferredAnswer": "\"Div soup\" is excessive, unnecessary nesting of `<div>` elements that makes code messy and hard to maintain.\n\n**How to fix:** (1) Only use `<div>` when you genuinely need to group content for CSS; (2) Use **semantic tags** instead (`<header>`, `<nav>`, `<main>`, `<section>`, `<footer>`); (3) Remove any `<div>` that doesn't serve a clear purpose."
    }
  ]
